    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, with an extended overhang, the torque experienced by the cantilevered balcony increases considerably, leading to larger stresses at the internal connection point. If the design is off (say, due to less material strength than required, improper support connection, or unexpected geometry changes), then it could fail under the unexpected heavy load. Just like columns in static equilibrium must be able to resist not only their own weight but also any superimposed loads, the connection at the wall in a cantilevered balcony assembly is engineered to handle both the structural weight and peak loads, including weather conditions, occupancy, and potential seismic activities. To counter this, the wall-ceiling assembly must be designed with a margin of safety, typically by choosing materials with a higher load-bearing capacity, and by using connection hardware capable of yielding or \"blowing off the walls\" under excessive loads before reaching a point of total structural failure. Detailing such as redundant connections and fail-safe designs may also be implemented, making it possible for the connection to redistribute loads and failure modes to prevent loss of whole structure integrity. Regular inspections, maintenance, and reinforcement as needed are also critical to ensuring ongoing stability.",
